GraphQL Field Aliases and Query Execution
Schema
type User {
    id: ID!
    name: String!
    age: Int!
}

type Query {
    users: [User!]!
    user(id: ID!): User
}

This schema exposes two top-level queries:

users → Returns a list of users.
user(id) → Returns a single user by its ID.
Query
query {
  users {
    id
    name
  }

  firstUser: user(id: "1") {
    age
  }

  secondUser: user(id: "2") {
    age
  }
}
Step 1: GraphQL parses the query

The GraphQL parser converts the query into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST).

The root fields are:

Query
│
├── users
├── firstUser -> user(id: "1")
└── secondUser -> user(id: "2")

Notice that firstUser and secondUser are aliases, not actual schema fields.

The actual schema field is still:

user(id: ID!)
Step 2: GraphQL validates the query

The validator checks:

Does users exist on Query? ✅
Does user exist on Query? ✅
Are the arguments correct? ✅
Do id, name, and age exist on User? ✅

Since everything matches the schema, execution begins.

Why aliases are required

Suppose we wrote:

query {
  user(id: "1") {
    age
  }

  user(id: "2") {
    age
  }
}

This is invalid.

Why?

Both fields have the same response name:

user
user

but they have different arguments.

If GraphQL allowed this, the response would have to look like:

{
    "user": ?
}

Should user contain the first user or the second one?

There is no unambiguous answer.

Therefore GraphQL throws:

Fields "user" conflict because they have differing arguments.
Aliases solve this problem

Aliases rename the field only in the response.

firstUser: user(id: "1")
secondUser: user(id: "2")

Internally GraphQL still calls the user resolver.

The aliases simply tell GraphQL to place the results under different keys.

Response:

{
    "firstUser": { ... },
    "secondUser": { ... }
}
Step 3: Resolver execution

GraphQL now executes each top-level field independently.

Conceptually:

users := Query.Users()

firstUser := Query.User("1")

secondUser := Query.User("2")

The order is not guaranteed by the GraphQL specification. Since these fields are independent, many GraphQL implementations may execute them concurrently.

Step 4: Resolver returns Go objects

Suppose the resolver returns

&model.User{
    ID: "1",
    Name: "John Doe",
    Age: 30,
}

This object contains all three fields.

User
├── ID
├── Name
└── Age
Step 5: GraphQL selects only requested fields

For

user(id: "1") {
    age
}

GraphQL ignores

id
name

and serializes only

age

Result:

{
    "age": 30
}

Even though the resolver returned the complete object.

Why GraphQL behaves this way

The client specifies exactly what data it wants.

The server only serializes those requested fields.

Benefits:

No over-fetching
No under-fetching
Different clients can request different subsets of the same object

Example:

Mobile app:

user(id: "1") {
    name
}

Web app:

user(id: "1") {
    id
    name
    age
}

Both use the same resolver.

Final response construction

After all resolvers finish, GraphQL combines the results into a single JSON response.

Query
│
├── users
│     ↓
│     [
│       {id, name},
│       {id, name}
│     ]
│
├── firstUser
│     ↓
│     {age}
│
└── secondUser
      ↓
      {age}

Final response:

{
  "data": {
    "users": [
      {
        "id": "1",
        "name": "John Doe"
      },
      {
        "id": "2",
        "name": "Jane Smith"
      }
    ],
    "firstUser": {
      "age": 30
    },
    "secondUser": {
      "age": 25
    }
  }
}
Key Takeaways
Every GraphQL query starts execution from the root type (Query, Mutation, or Subscription).
Each top-level field invokes its corresponding resolver.
The same field cannot appear multiple times with different arguments unless aliases are used.
Aliases rename fields only in the response; they do not change the schema or which resolver is called.
Resolvers may return complete objects, but GraphQL serializes only the fields requested by the client.
After all requested fields are resolved, GraphQL assembles them into a single JSON response that mirrors the structure of the query.